mponents settle into a neat product arrangement in the foreground. A beige tower stands on the left, flanked by a small grey speaker. In the center, a beige CRT monitor faces forward with a black screen, a white keyboard directly in front of it, and a white mouse to the right. On the far right, another grey speaker stands beside a colorful “CD-ROM” software or hardware box. Behind and beneath the display are stacked Lexmark boxes, including boxes marked “1100,” while the store shelves in the background are packed with hanging accessories, boxed products, and additional desktop systems. The translucent white feature list continues to overlay the scene, partially covering the products as the package is shown.\n\nThe store background briefly clears to reveal more shelves and counters: printers, small electronics, boxed accessories, and another monitor on a shelf to the right. Then three boxed items float prominently against a softly blurred store background. On the left is a yellow box labeled “LinkScan,” showing a small flat scanner-like device. In the middle is a blue “Lexmark ImageWave” box with a large photo of a smiling person. On the right is a yellow-and-white Lexmark printer box labeled “1100,” visually matching the spoken offer of a printer or scanner choice.\n\nLarge promotional text fills the center over the store interior: “FREE” appears in big red letters, with “Internet Access” below in large yellow letters. Small text underneath says “See Store for Details.” The background remains the computer store, slightly out of focus, with rows of equipment and boxed displays visible.\n\nThe full computer package returns against the blurred store background: tower on the left, monitor and keyboard in the center, speakers on both sides, mouse at the keyboard’s right edge, and the CD-ROM box on the right. Above it, yellow text reads, “Includes 1 Year Warranty.”\n\nThe commercial ends on a blue graphic screen with the Computer Renaissance logo at the top. Beneath it, w